This is an implementation of the `Utf8Span` type as described at https://github.com/dotnet/corefxlab/issues/2350. The goal of this type is to have a proper type that can represent a slice of guaranteed well-formed immutable UTF-8 data and to allow callers to perform text-like operations on that data. Some code samples follow.

```cs
/*
 * splitting: both syntaxes below are valid
 */

Utf8Span name = u"Doe, John";
(Utf8Span lastName, Utf8Span firstName) = name.Split(',', Utf8StringSplitOptions.TrimEntries);

foreach (Utf8Span entry in name.Split(',', Utf8StringSplitOptions.TrimEntries)
{
    /* do something */
}

/*
 * text manipulation
 */

Span<byte> asUpper = GetScratchBuffer();

int bytesWritten = name.ToUpperInvariant(asUpper);
if (bytesWritten < 0) { /* FAIL */ }

asUpper = asUpper.Slice(0, bytesWritten);

/*
 * simple equality comparison
 */

Utf8Span httpVerb = GetVerb();
if (httpVerb == u"GET") { /* do something */ }
else if (httpVerb == u"POST") { /* do something else */ }

/*
 * p/invoke
 */

[DllImport(...)]
private static extern int ExportedFunction(byte* pbData, int cbData);

Utf8Span theSpan = GetSpan();
fixed (byte* pbPinned = theSpan) // can be pinned as a byte*
{
    ExportedFunction(pbPinned, theSpan.Bytes.Length);
}

/*
 * searching and slicing
 * (if you don't want to use the Split* methods)
 */

Utf8Span theSpan = u"8â™¦ Aâ™¦ 10â™  2â™¥ Qâ™¥";

if (theSpan.Contains('â™ ')) {
    Console.WriteLine("You have a spade!");
}

if (theSpan.TryFind('â™¥', out Range match))
{
    Console.WriteLine("You have a heart!");

    // 'match' is a System.Range representing where in the original span the search term was found
    Utf8Span theHeart = theSpan[match]; // == "â™¥"
    Utf8Span before = theSpan[..match.Start]; // == "8â™¦ Aâ™¦ 10â™  2"
    Utf8Span after = theSpan[match.End..]; // == " Qâ™¥"
}
else
{
    Console.WriteLine("You do not have a heart.");
}

// Below line will throw an exception because it's trying to split within a multi-byte subsequence,
// and the resulting slice would end up containing ill-formed UTF-8 data.
Utf8Span slice = ((Utf8Span)u"ðŸ˜€")[1..];
```

Unit tests are located at https://github.com/GrabYourPitchforks/corefx/tree/dev2/utf8string/src/System.Utf8String.Experimental/tests/System and will be merged into corefx as a separate PR.

Work items that aren't part of this PR, since I was trying to keep the size manageable:

 * Also changing `Utf8String` to have the "correct by construction" semantics at https://github.com/dotnet/corefxlab/issues/2350, including modifications to its ctors, removal of the `this[int]` indexer, and getting its API to have parity with `Utf8Span`.
 * Removing `Char8` from the repo entirely.
 * Optimizing the `Utf8Span` code paths to avoid allocations / transcoding and instead to call into ICU if available on the current OS. On Windows, we'll need to consider how the CLDR tables carried by ICU differ from the tables carried by NLS.

_Note to reviewers: This API has not yet been approved. That shouldn't block checkin, as this whole feature is behind a feature flag. Once the entire feature is run through LDM and the design review committee we can react to API changes and remove the feature flag._

